n_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":53274,"username":"EmerqldWither","name":"","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/emerqldwither/{size}/226176_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":64968,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch/493750/6","custom_user_title":"Programmer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3544425,"name":"Emre ","username":"DukeEmree","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dukeemree/{size}/251833_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-01T22:06:38.053Z","cooked":"<p>We have this too but we have position errors sometimes. So it didn’t work</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":13,"updated_at":"2025-03-01T22:06:38.053Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":123,"readers_count":122,"score":24.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":493750,"topic_slug":"how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch","display_username":"Emre ","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":24594,"username":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","name":"SLAB-Mr.Thomas","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/slab-mr.thomas/{size}/182153_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":64968,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch/493750/7","custom_user_title":"Programmer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3544609,"name":"Joe Ross","username":"Joe_Ross","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/joe_ross/{size}/37_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-02T02:55:11.488Z","cooked":"<p>That sounds like how most people want limit switches to work. Can you explain what you want to happen?</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":13,"updated_at":"2025-03-02T02:55:11.488Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":110,"readers_count":109,"score":27.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":493750,"topic_slug":"how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch","display_username":"Joe Ross","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":64968,"username":"DukeEmree","name":"Emre ","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dukeemree/{size}/251833_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":true,"admin":false,"staff":true,"user_id":65,"hidden":false,"trust_level":4,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch/493750/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3544685,"name":"Emre ","username":"DukeEmree","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dukeemree/{size}/251833_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-02T05:29:09.643Z","cooked":"<p>When limit switch going true to false(elevator trying to go up) elevator motors stops(because I have stop motors command too). I want to use limit switch with stop motors for security. If is it okay I will set software limit to 0 and sensor position to 0 when going down. So it should stop even if I have position error right?</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":13,"updated_at":"2025-03-02T05:29:09.643Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":100,"readers_count":99,"score":20.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":493750,"topic_slug":"how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch","display_username":"Emre ","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":65,"username":"Joe_Ross","name":"Joe Ross","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/joe_ross/{size}/37_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":64968,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch/493750/9","custom_user_title":"Programmer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3545283,"name":"Dan","username":"tekdemo","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/tekdemo/{size}/138330_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-03T00:23:58.111Z","cooked":"<p>If you have positioning errors due to mechanical issues (slipped belts, skipping teeth, etc), it’s generally better to fix <em>that</em>. Not being able to trust your soft limits is very suboptimal.</p>
<p>The problem you’ll run into is that if your system is slipping relative to the encoder, soft limits will wind up stopping you from contacting the switch, and your system will drift far away from it. When this happens, you then need to run code that intentionally ignores the soft limits.<br>
If you’re fortunate, the system will slip in a way that lets you hit the limit. However, now you may as well not have soft limits at all; The switch will be the actual reason the system is stopping.</p>
<p>If you’re coding soft limits, you don’t want to stop commands or overwrite outputs directly. You want to constrain possible outputs from arbitrary commands. This is not ideal, as it conflicts with the way the motors handle input.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">//set motors directly
motor.setPower(-1)
// halt motor if switch is pressed
if(limitswitch) motor.stop()
</code></pre>
<p>This is the same problem, but with commands (which will break sequences too)</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">//Do driver things
driver.a().onTrue( elevator.run(-1))
//Have a trigger panic and stop things
Trigger(()-&gt; elevator.limitswitch == isPressed()).onTrue( elevator.stop())
</code></pre>
<p>The problem is that you only want to have the Limit switch do things if you’re going <em>toward</em> the limit switch, but want to let it try and move away. Because of this, you don’t want to interrupt commands without checking direction. However, velocities are noisy, and so you’ll often wind up interrupting commands when you don’t mean to.</p>
<p>So, instead, what you want to do is constrain inputs based on the limit switches, like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">//Tell the elevator which way it's going
elevator.setPower(-1)

//and in elevator.SetPower, handle limits
public void setPower(double power){
if(bottom_limit==pressed) power = MathUtil.clamp(power,0,1);
if(top_limit==pressed) power = MathUtil.clamp(power,-1,0);
motor.setPower(power)
}
</code></pre>
<p>and then use this function instead of directly writing motor output. This will allow you to leave the limit switch by going up, and will not allow you to go down if you’re hitting the limit switch.</p>
<p>You should be able to have the motor controller do this for you: I believe all <span class="abbreviation">FRC<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="FIRST Robotics Competition"></template></span> motor controllers have a “limit switch” pin that you can hook your switch to. It runs this clamp logic directly on the motor controller for you.<br>
They also have an API to ask if the switch is pressed.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":13,"updated_at":"2025-03-03T00:25:16.545Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":81,"readers_count":80,"score":21.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":493750,"topic_slug":"how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch","display_username":"Dan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44763,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2811 Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/how-to-reset-elevator-with-limitswitch/493750/10","custom_user_title":"2811 Programming Mentor","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3545798,"name":"Emre ","username":"DukeEmree","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dukeemree/{size}/251833_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-03T14:06:27.424Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks thats what I need</p>
